Hello @deleted-role 

Subnet `v0.9.3` has been merged to main. This is a mandatory update for validators, and we will be updating the weights version hyperparameter to `93` roughly on Wednesday, August 21, 2024 8:00:00 AM. 

**Change log:**

- Weight setting upgraded to new commit reveal feature
- Adjustments to Healthcheck API

As always, please let us know if you have any questions or concerns. 

Note that commit reveal won't be enabled until after the weights version hyperparameter has been changed to `93`. This update makes it such that the validator checks the subnet hyperparameters to determine whether to use `set_weights` or `commit_weights`.

This is also the last scheduled update before subnet `v1.0.0`. Next step--putting the subnet into production! 🚀

Cheers!

Hello sn14,
Hello @m4k1 (SN105) [τ, τ],

This is Maja from the white hat validator initiative. An effort is being made to reduce the effort required to debug malfunctioning validator instances and in order to do that, I need a small piece of information from you today.

If a validator of your subnet malfunctions somehow (doesn't set weights or sets weights incorrectly), the operator will log into via ssh to the environment where the validator is running. That's a clear first step, but then, what commands should he issue in order to collect diagnostic information, which would be helpful to the developers of the subnet in troubleshooting the problem? The most obvious choice here would be to collect logs, but is there any other information (about software/hardware configuration or current state of the validator, for example) that should be retrieved in order to provide a cohesive report? Perhaps newest entries from a local database need to be dumped to properly understand the state in which the validator happens to be during the suspected period?

As the commands for retrieving the logs and other information are very subnet-specifc (some use pm2, some use docker, some a docker-compose-in-docker-compose...), I'd like to ask you to, in reply to this message, list the commands that you recommend the validator operators execute to retrieve the information that you might find useful during debugging.

Hello @Majazreef!

SN14 has logging enabled on multiple tiers. SUCCESS, INFO and WARNING logs are a useful first step to seeing what is wrong, but validators and miners are also able to obtain an overview of their neuron's operations via INFO, DEBUG and TRACE logs (what level of logging you see can be adjusted in the .env). INFO denotes the most fundamental operations, DEBUG offers general insight into the result of each specific operation, and TRACE offers insight into the specifics of each operation carried out by the neuron. 

We also have a HealthCheck API in place that validators can query to obtain metrics and event logs to determine if their validator is running correctly. More information on this can be found in our docs here: https://docs.synapsec.ai/Validating/running_validator/#7-assessing-validator-health

Cheers!

Hi @ here: 

We will be shortly upgrading the testnet chain with Dynamic TAO. 
In order to prepare testnet subnet for this change read this document: https://docs.bittensor.com/dynamic-tao

It is essential that your upgrade your Bittensor version to work with the new chain (we will inform you when that has been done) or else some of the common commands your miners/validators use i.e. like `subtensor.metagraph` to retrieve the latest network state ***will fail***. Please read the above document explaining how you can change to the correct branch and avoid this situation.

Aside from the upgrade to the SDK and CLI, you should experience very little change in the actual consensus of your network. Why? because the normal TAO staked on your validators will still be counted in each mechanism. Within the next month or more your subnet token will begin to have more effect on the dynamics of Yuma Consensus. We will be releasing more information on how this work technically later.

We will do our best to explain more about this upgrade and what you need to know at todays Novelty Search. Please come at the usual time of Thursday, January 9, 2025 3:00:00 PM today.

Best
